[1] Montana mule deer
Date: Mon 3 Dec 2018
Source: Great Falls Tribune [edited]
https://eu.greatfallstribune.com/story/news/2018/12/03/seven-more-deer-test-positive-deadly-wasting-disease/2197143002/


A total of 7 more deer shot by hunters in Montana have turned up positive for chronic wasting disease (CWD), a fatal disease of the nervous system that's reduced deer herds in other states by as much as 40%. All were mule deer bucks.

Three of the deer were shot in Valley and Daniels counties where deer had yet to test positive for CWD. Those counties are located on the Hi-line along the state's northern border with Canada. In Valley County, a positive deer was harvested 18 mi [approx. 29 km] west of Opheim. In Daniels County, a positive deer was shot 15 mi [approx. 24 km] northwest of Scobey near the Canadian border, and another just inside the Fort Peck Reservation.

"This is our biggest batch of positives we've had in the last 2 years, so it's significant in that regard," said Greg Lemon, a Montana Fish, Wildlife and Parks [FWP] spokesman. "What we don't know from this is what the prevalence is within the population of where the positives were found."

The other 4 positive deer were shot in Blaine County, also on the Hi-line, and Carbon County in south central Montana. Deer had previously tested positive for CWD in those areas.

CWD is a relatively rare disease that affects the nervous system of deer, elk and moose. It is similar to a group of nervous system diseases known as transmissible spongiform encephalopathies such as scrapie in sheep. Infected animals can appear healthy for many years before showing symptoms such as walking repetitive courses, inability to coordinate voluntary muscular movements, wide-based stance and subtle head tremors.

"My understanding is none of them were symptomatic," Lemon said of the 7 Montana deer that tested positive for CWD. Animals with CWD often are not symptomatic until they are close to death, Lemon added.

No convincing evidence exists that the agent of CWD affects humans, according to FWP. However, FWP advises hunters not to shoot animals that appear sick or eat meat from suspect animals. The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention advises that deer shot in CWD-positive areas be tested before the meat is consumed. FWP also has rules in place in these areas that restrict the transportation of spinal columns and brain tissue of CWD-positive animals.

"We're not surprised to find it," Lemon said. "It's probably been here for a little while." From 1998 to 2016, Montana tested more than 17 000 wild deer, elk and moose for CWD. There were no positive tests until the fall of 2017. A total of 10 deer harvested on the Hi-Line have now tested positive for CWD, Lemon said.

This year [2018], FWP conducted CWD surveillance across the HI-line during the general big game hunting season, which ended [25 Nov 2018]. Hunters brought animals to check stations where lymph nodes were taken out for testing. The purpose of the surveillance is to better understand where the disease is and how widespread, Lemon said. "CWD has the capability to have long-term impacts to deer herds," Lemon said. "We need all the information we can get so we can be as informed as we can with management efforts."

Other states have seen 40% declines in deer numbers as a result of CWD, Lemon said.

Management efforts to slow the spread in Montana could include adjusting regulations to thin the deer population in areas where deer congregate such as around alfalfa fields or center irrigation pivots that spray crops with water. "Those are a couple of ways we could manage it but it's not an eradication situation," Lemon said. "So we're not trying to eliminate herds of deer, but we are going to be active in how we manage it." Samples from the surveillance efforts are coming in weekly, and more test results are expected by the middle of next week, Lemon said.

Once the CWD sample results are collected, FWP will decide what to do next, Lemon said. That may include expanding current CWD-positive areas and CWD transportation restriction zones.

[Byline: Karl Puckett]
